T1  - CHARACTERISTICS OF INTERPERSONAL RELATIONS IN MUNICIPAL GOVERNMENT
AU  - Holloman, Charles R.
Y1  - 1973/12/01
PY  - 1973
DA  - 1973/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/254702
DO  - 10.5465/254702
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 691
EP  - 695
VL  - 16
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article discusses a study on interpersonal relations in municipal government. The author defines interpersonal relations as the interaction between two or more persons who are directly involved with each other in the context of their work environment. The subjects of the study were the city manager and the directors of departments and staff agencies of a large southern U.S. city. The subjects completed Hall and William?s Personnel Relations Survey. According to the author, results showed that significant increases were effected by the willingness of managers to seek and maintain more open relationships with their subordinates, their colleagues, and their superiors.
AB  - The article discusses a study on interpersonal relations in municipal government. The author defines interpersonal relations as the interaction between two or more persons who are directly involved with each other in the context of their work environment. The subjects of the study were the city manager and the directors of departments and staff agencies of a large southern U.S. city. The subjects completed Hall and William?s Personnel Relations Survey. According to the author, results showed that significant increases were effected by the willingness of managers to seek and maintain more open relationships with their subordinates, their colleagues, and their superiors.
